# Simple wave motion and the Wave Equation {#sec-ch6-wavemotion}

*Textbook link: Tipler and Mosca, Section 15.1*

A wave is a means by which energy and momentum are carried through space, without transporting matter.  When we consider a medium which carries a wave, the particles of that material oscillate about a mean position, but have an average displacement of zero; *i.e.* they always return to their starting position.  A wave can be of any shape - there is no requirement for a wave to be sinusoidal, though this is the simplest shape which we can consider mathematically.

We also consider waves to be either **transverse**; where the displacement of the medium is perpendicular to the direction of wave propagation (*e.g.* a wave travelling along a string), or they can be **longitudinal**; where the displacement of the medium is parallel to the direction of propagation (*e.g.* a sound wave passing through air).


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![An animation to show the propagation of a wave through a material arising from an organised transverse oscillation of many particles. The two marked particles only move up and down, but the net effect of the organised motion is a propagation of energy to the right.](visualisations/ch6-transversewave2.gif){#fig-ch6-transversewaveill1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::

::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![An animation to show the propagation of a wave through a material arising from an organised longitudinal oscillation of many particles. The marked particle now  moves in the direction of propagation, but oscillates around a fixed point; the net effect of the organised motion is again a propagation of energy to the right.](visualisations/ch6-longitudinalwave1.gif){#fig-ch6-longitudinalwaveill1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::



### A note on transverse waves {-}

In contrast with longitudinal waves, the medium carrying a transverse wave is displaced perpendicular to the direction of travel. This gives rise to the phenomenon of **polarisation**.  A *plane of polarisation* is defined as a plane containing the displacement direction and the direction of propagation.  For any given transverse wave, two orthogonal independent polarisations are possible.  All other polarisations may be constructed from weighted combinations of these two basic polarisations.  For electromagnetic waves, it is the **electric field vector** which defines the plane of polarisation in combination with the direction of propagation.  We will revisit these properties of transverse waves as we go through our discussion.

## Wave pulses {#sec-ch6-wavepulses}

Where a wave is a sustained periodic disturbance which propagates energy through a medium, a **wave pulse** in contrast is any localised non-periodic disturbance propagating an energy pulse through the medium.  A typical pulse is shown in @fig-ch6-wavepulse1.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A wave pulse propagating through a system at velocity $v$; this causes a temporary transverse disturbance of molecules in the system from their origin.](visualisations/ch6-wavepulse1.gif){#fig-ch6-wavepulse1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::



We illustrate a pulse graphically as any function defined as $y = f(x)$, where the $+x$ direction is the direction of propagation of the pulse.  If the pulse propagates without changing shape, it becomes convenient to consider a moving reference frame within which the pulse is stationary; *i.e.* rather than imagining the pulse moving to the right along fixed axes, we keep the pulse stationary in our view and move the axes to the left.

In the moving frame then, the pulse is described as $y^\prime = f(x^\prime)$ for all times, because the pulse does not change its shape.

We can inter convert between the two frames of reference by the relation:

$$
x = x^\prime + vt
$${#eq-ch6-refframeconvert1}

...where $v$ is the velocity of the pulse.  This allows us to convert the position in the moving reference frame, $x^\prime$, back to the position in the fixed reference frame by adding the distance $vt$.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Rather than imagining a moving wave pulse, we can consider it from the reference frame of the wave pulse; in this example the wave pulse is stationary, but the space moves past it.](visualisations/ch6-wavepulse2.gif){#fig-ch6-referenceframes1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::

::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A wave pulse propagating through a system at velocity $v$; this causes a temporary transverse disturbance of molecules in the system from their origin.](visualisations/ch6-wavepulse3.svg){#fig-ch6-referenceframes2 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::


If the shape of the pulse in the moving frame is defined as $y^\prime = f(x^\prime)$ we can use @eq-ch6-refframeconvert1 to find the shape of the pulse in the static frame, $y$:

$$
\begin{array}{rcl}
y &=& f(x^\prime)\\
&=& f(x - vt)
\end{array}
$${#eq-ch6-refframeconvert2}

The relation described in @eq-ch6-refframeconvert2 describes a wave moving to the **RIGHT**; for a pulse moving to the **left**, $v$ becomes negative, and hence:

$$
y = f(x + vt)
$$

The function $y = f(x \pm vt)$ is known as the **wave function**; it describes the displacement of the medium, whether the transverse displacement of a string or the longitudinal displacement of air molecules in a sound wave.^[It may seem counter intuitive that, for a wave moving with positive $v$in the $+x$ direction, we subtract $vt$; but try thinking this way: after time $t$, the wave will have advanced further to the right. If, after one second, the shape of the wave has its peak at $x_a$, after three seconds, the peak will have advanced to $x_b = x_a + vt$; **however**, the value of the wavefunction at $x_a$ at this new time ($x_a^\prime$) will have come from the value of the wavefunction three seconds earlier, to the **left** of the point; i.e. $x_a^\prime = x_a - vt$].

The *wave function* is a solution of the **wave equation** (@eq-ch6-waveequation1):^[The $\partial$ symbol refers to *partial differentiation*.]

$$
\frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2} = \frac{1}{v^2} \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-waveequation1}

**Any** function in the form $y = f(x \pm vt)$ is a solution of this wave equation; *i.e.* the wave equation describes the uniform propagation of **any** displacement, provided it does not change shape as it travels. There are numerous examples of such functions, including:

* $y = \exp(x-vt)^2$
* $y = \frac{\sin(x-vt)}{x-vt}$
* $y = \cos (x+vt)$

## Deriving the wave equation {#sec-ch6-derivingwaveequation}

To better understand the wave equation, it is useful to know its derivation. To do this, we shall first consider a segment of string from a curved part of a wave pulse (@fig-ch6-waveeqnderiv1):


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Here we consider a small portion of a string carrying a wave pulse; the tension in the string $F$ is constant throughout, but resolving the forces via the angles $\theta_1$ and $\theta_2$ allows us to determine the equation of motion on this segment.](visualisations/LaTeX/ch6-waveequationderiv1.svg){#fig-ch6-waveeqnderiv1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::



The length of this segment is $\approx \Delta x$ (for small angles), and the mass of this segment of string $m = \mu \Delta x$ (where $\mu$ is the mass per unit length).  As we are considering a transverse wave, this segment of string will move vertically, and all forces acting on the segment arise from the tension force within the string. We can determine these forces by resolving the horizontal and vertical components of this force $F$ using the parameters laid out in @fig-ch6-waveeqnderiv1.

By considering the net vertical force acting on this segment:

$$
\begin{array}{rcll}
\sum F &=& F \sin \theta_2 - F \sin \theta_1 &\\
&=& F \left( \tan \theta_2 - \tan \theta_1 \right) & \textsf{for small angles}
\end{array}
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv1}

We can also determine an expression for the slope, $S$, of the segment of string at a given point:

$$
S = \tan \theta = \frac{\partial y}{\partial x}
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv2}

This means we can now express the overall force acting on the segment in terms of the slope of the segment at its start and end points (assuming small angles!) by combining @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv1 and @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv2 :

$$
\sum F = F(S_2 - S_1) = F \Delta S
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv3}

The quantity $F\Delta S$ in @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv3 is the net force acting on the segment; so we can now apply Newton's second law:

$$
F\Delta S = m a = \mu \Delta x \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv4}

...or, to rearrange:

$$
\frac{\Delta S}{\Delta x} = \frac{\mu}{F} \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv5}

Since the slope $\Delta S$ of the segment is the 'rate of change of $y$ with respect to $x$' (@eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv2), we can redefine the term in @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv4; in the limit, as $\Delta x \rightarrow 0$:

$$
\frac{\Delta S}{\Delta x} \approx \frac{\partial S}{\partial x} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \left( \frac{\partial y}{\partial x} \right) = \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2}
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv6}

Finally, by combining this result in @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv6 with the result in @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv5), we obtain the wave equation for a stretched string (@eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv7):

$$
\frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2} = \frac{\mu}{F} \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv7}

As we mentioned in @sec-ch6-wavepulses, any function of the form $y = f(x \pm vt)$ will be a solution to the wave @eq-ch6-waveeqnderiv7.  In the case of the string, the solution will solve the wave equation provided that $v^2 = \frac{F}{\mu}$.

## The wave equation - proof by substitution {#sec-ch6-waveequationproof2}

In this section, we will show the proof of the wave equation which we determined graphically in @sec-ch6-derivingwaveequation.  Here we will use *partial differentiation*, explaining the $\partial$ notation we have already seen in this work.^[Partial differentiation is needed when we have multivariate expressions. We can only differentiate one variable at a time, so *partial* differentiation indicates that we are holding all other variables constant.  In our wave equations, we have position and time variables, so when differentiating $x$ with respect to $y$, we are holding the time $t$ constant.]

Let's work through this step by step:

1. Consider the general function $y  = \cos(x - vt)$.  Differentiate this first with respect to $x$:

$$
\frac{\partial y}{\partial x} = -\sin(x - vt)
$$

The second derivative therefore becomes:

$$
\frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2} = -\cos(x - vt)
$${#eq-ch6-wavederivsubs1}

2. Now we differentiate with respect to time $t$:

$$
\frac{\partial y}{\partial t} = v\sin(x - vt)
$$

... and find the second derivative:

$$
\frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2} = -v^2 \cos(x - vt)
$${#eq-ch6-wavederivsubs2}

3. We can now combine @eq-ch6-wavederivsubs1 and @eq-ch6-wavederivsubs2 to eliminate the term $\cos(x - vt)$, we obtain the wave equation as required:

$$
\frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2} = \frac{1}{v^2} \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-wavederivsubs3}

Through unpacking of @eq-ch6-wavederivsubs3 we can uncover how it might be adapted to obtain wave equations for other systems.  The term $x$ represents the direction of propagation of the wave, while $y$ represents the disturbance of the particle carrying the wave (in the case of a transverse wave, this is perpendicular to the direction of propagation).

For longitudinal sound waves, @eq-ch6-wavederivsubs3 becomes:

$$
\frac{\partial^2 s}{\partial x^2} = \frac{1}{v_s^2} \frac{\partial^2 s}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-wavederivsubs4}


In this example, $s$ is the displacement of molecules of the medium parallel to the direction of the propagation, while $v_s$ is the velocity of sound in the medium.

For electromagnetic waves, @eq-ch6-wavederivsubs3 becomes either:


$$
\frac{\partial^2 E_z}{\partial x^2} = \frac{1}{c^2} \frac{\partial^2 E_z}{\partial t^2}
(\#eq-ch6-wavederivsubs5)
$${#eq-}

...or

$$
\frac{\partial^2 B_y}{\partial x^2} = \frac{1}{c^2} \frac{\partial^2 B_y}{\partial t^2}
$${#eq-ch6-wavederivsubs5b}

...where $E_z$ and $B_y$ are the transverse components of the electric and magnetic field vectors (we will discuss this further later), and $c$ is the speed of light.

**Note**: The speed of propagation cannot be deduced from the wave equation, instead it must be obtained from a model of the system concerned.


## The Phase Velocity - the velocity of waves {#sec-ch6-phasevelocity}

We define the phase velocity as the speed of propagation of any particular point on a wave. Since the wave propagates without changing shape, it does not matter which point we pick.

The phase velocity will depend on a combination of the elastic and inertial terms.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A reminder that every point in a wave pulse here moves at the same velocity $v$, such that the shape of the pulse is not changed.](visualisations/ch6-phasevelocity1.svg){#fig-ch6-phasevelocity1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::



For waves travelling on a string the phase velocity can be found from the tension in the string ($F$) and the linear mass density (mass per unit length) of the string ($\mu$):

$$
v = \sqrt{\frac{F}{\mu}}
$$

This has parallels for sound waves in a fluid, with phase velocity found from the bulk modulus $B$ (a factor describing the fluid's resistance to compression) and the equilibrium density $\rho$ of the fluid:

$$
v_s = \sqrt{\frac{B}{\rho}}
$$

We can go further to look at the propagation of sound waves in an isotropic solid (solid of constant composition) - however we can only use this to consider a thin section, not a bulk solid (this is an acceptable model for considering earth tremors in the Earth's crust).  This time the phase velocity depends on the density of the solid $\rho$ and either the Young's modulus ($Y$, for longitudinal P waves) or the shear modulus ($G$, for transverse S waves):

$$
v_s = \sqrt{\frac{Y}{\rho}} \textrm{or} \sqrt{\frac{G}{\rho}}
$$

These equations describe how  wave phase velocities can be determined in solids and liquids; in a gas, we need to use other parameters, however the core relationship is still familiar:

$$
v_s = \sqrt{\frac{\gamma RT}{M}} =  \sqrt{\frac{\gamma k_{\mathrm{B}}T}{m}}
$$

Here, the terms $R$, $T$ and $M$ refer to the gas constant (units J K^-1^ mol^-1^), absolute temperature (units K) and the molar mass of the gas (units kg mol^-1^) respectively^[Note that the molar mass is expressed in kg mol^-1^ here, rather than the more common g mol^-1^ ; the reason for this is to ensure continuity and present everything in SI units.], while $k_{\textrm{B}}$ and $m$ refer to the Boltzmann constant (units J K^-1^) and the mass of an individual gas molecule (units kg).

Finally, we can obtain a similar expression for the phase velocity of light waves:

$$
c = \sqrt{\frac{1}{\mu_0 \epsilon_0}}
$$

...where $\mu_0$ and $\epsilon_0$ are the permeability of free space and the permittivity of free space respectively.

## Simple wave summary {#sec-ch6-summary}

In this chapter, we have introduced the principle of waves and the wave equation.  Waves carry energy and momentum through space by localised organised oscillations without net transport of matter.  They can be transverse (oscillation perpendicular to direction of propagation) or longitudinal (oscillation parallel to direction of propagation), or can have a more complex displacement pattern.  Waves do not have to be sinusoidal, and can have any shape.

Any travelling wave can be described by the function in the form of $y = f(x \pm vt)$ which satisfies the wave equation, relating the displacement of the medium ($y$) to the position of the wave ($x$) and the phase velocity ($v$).

$$
\frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2} = \frac{1}{v^2} \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2}
$$

Remember that the phase velocity cannot be predicted from the wave equation, but depends on the physics of the system. It generally results from a consideration of the elastic and inertial properties of the system. For waves on a string, $v = \sqrt{\frac{F}{\mu}}$, where $F$ is the tension in the string and $\mu$ is the mass per unit length (linear mass density).

# Harmonic Waves {#sec-ch6a-harmonicwaves}

*Textbook link: Tipler and Mosca, Section 15.2*

A *harmonic wave* is a general term for a wave which, at some instant of time, can be described by a sinusoidal function (*i.e.* it is a sine or a cosine function).  They are the simplest of waves to consider, and we will devote this chapter to exploring their properties.

## Transverse sine and cosine waves {#sec-ch6a-sinecosine}

If we consider a string which is excited by a tuning fork or other object undergoing simple harmonic motion (SHM), we can imagine the shape of the save on the string at some instant of time appearing as a sine or a cosine wave (depending on our choice of origin) (@fig-ch6a-transversesine1):


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A sine wave in a string created by an oscillating particle.  The wavelength $\lambda$ is shown for one complete cycle, while the amplitude $A$ is defined as the maximum deviation from the origin point.](visualisations/ch6a-transversesine1.gif){#fig-ch6a-transversesine1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::


This sinusoidal appearance is known as a **harmonic wave**.  Each point on the string oscillates up and down with the same frequency as the driving frequency.  During the period $T$, the wave moves through distance $\lambda$:

$$
v = \frac{\lambda}{T} = f\lambda
$${#eq-ch6a-tranversesine1}

...where $v$ is the phase velocity of the wave and $f$ is the frequency in hertz (Hz), and  $\lambda$ defined as the **wavelength** *i.e.* the spacial repeat distance of the wave.

A harmonic wave has a unique frequency and wavelength, and other waves (*e.g.* wave pulses) may be regarded as a superposition of many harmonic waves of different frequencies (we will discuss the Fourier analysis of this later).

At any instant in time, the wave can be described by the relation in @eq-ch6a-tranversesine2:

$$
y = A \sin(kx + \delta)
$${#eq-ch6a-tranversesine2}

...where $A$ is the amplitude of the wave and $\delta$ is the phase constant.  Let's now choose the origin so that $\delta$ is equal to zero (*i.e.* there is no phase constant).  Now we can show the periodic condition in @eq-ch6a-tranversesine3:

$$
\sin kx = \sin k(x+\lambda)
$${#eq-ch6a-tranversesine3}

Here we specify the periodic condition; the amplitude (and phase!) at position $x$ is equal to the amplitude (and phase!) at position $x$ **plus one wavelength**.  Because this is a sine function, we know that, in order to achieve this condition, the value $k\lambda$ must be equal to $2\pi$:

$$
\begin{array}{rcl}
\sin \theta &=& \sin \left( \theta + 2\pi \right)\\
\sin kx &=& \sin \left( kx + k\lambda\right) = \sin \left( kx + 2\pi \right) \\
k\lambda &=& 2\pi
\end{array}
$${#eq-ch6a-tranvsersesine3b}

This allows us to give a value for $k$ (@eq-ch6a-tranversesine4):

$$
k = \frac{2\pi}{\lambda}
$${#eq-ch6a-tranversesine4}

The parameter $k$ is defined as the **wave number** of the wave, in units radians per metre (rad m^-1^).

## Travelling waves {#sec-ch6a-travellingwaves}

The wave we showed in @sec-ch6a-sinecosine was a snapshot in time, so the wave was, in effect, static.  We instead wish to consider a travelling wave. To do this, instead of writing $x$ as in @eq-tranversesine2 with a phase difference, we rewrite with $x - vt$ (see @sec-ch6-wavepulses) to illustrate the time-dependent nature of the travelling wave.  @eq-tranversesine2 then becomes @eq-tranversesine5:

$$
y = A \sin k(x - vt) = A \sin (kx - kvt)
$${#eq-tranversesine5}

As we have described, $T$ is the period of the wave, so any point on the wave will oscillate up and down also with period $T$.  This means that, for the wave position at time $t$, it will return to the same state at time $(t+T)$.  We can therefore write @eq-tranversesine5 in terms of this period:

$$
\begin{array}{rcl}
y = A \sin \left( kx - kvt \right) &=& A \sin \left( kx - kv(t+T) \right) \\
&=& A \sin \left( kx - kvt - kvT \right)
\end{array}
$${#eq-ch6a-travelling2}

Applying the same reasoning as shown in @eq-ch6a-tranvsersesine3b, we are led to the result:

$$
kvT = 2\pi
$$

If we revisit our discussions on SHM (@sec-shm-freq-angularfreq) we defined the relationship between $T$ and $2\pi$ (@eq-ch1-definingomega1) as $T = \frac{2\pi}{\omega}$ (and also $\omega = 2\pi f$).  This allows us to define a number of factors as follows:

* **Phase velocity**:

$$
v = \frac{2\pi}{kT} = \frac{\omega}{k}
$${#eq-ch6a-phasevel1}

* **Travelling wave to the right**:

$$
y = A \sin \left( kx - kvt \right) = A \sin \left( kx - \omega t \right)
$${#eq-ch6a-travellingtoright1}

* **Travelling wave to the left**:

$$
y = A \sin \left( kx + kvt \right) = A \sin \left( kx + \omega t \right)
$${#eq-ch6a-travellingtoleft1}

It is worth noting for each of these factors:

1. The sign of $\omega$:
    * negative for waves travelling to right;
    * positive for waves travelling to left
1. The wave expressions can be shown to satisfy the wave equation by substitution.

## Complex representation of waves {#sec-ch6a-complexrep}

We introduced complex numbers for descriptions of oscillations; we can use the same treatment for our wave equations.  Just as $\sin(kx - \omega t)$ and $\cos(kx-\omega t)$ satisfy the wave equation, so too will $\mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i}(kx-\omega t)}$.  It is often convenient to write the wave expression in a complex form as shown in @eq-ch6a-wavecomplex1:

$$
y = A \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i}(kx-\omega t)}
$${#eq-ch6a-wavecomplex1}

In this expression, the sine wave is given by the 'imaginary' component of $y$, while the cosine part is given by the 'real' component.

## Energy carried by waves on a string {#sec-ch6a-energywavesstring}

Suppose we now have a string attached to an oscillating driver at one end.  As the driver oscillates, it imparts energy to the string at $x=0$ by:

1. Stretching the string to give it potential energy, and
1. imparting transverse speed to the string to increase its kinetic energy.

As the waves move along the string, so the energy is transported along the string.

### Potential energy of string segment {#sec-ch6a-peofstringsegment}

We now consider the same string segment as we showed in @fig-ch6-waveeqnderiv1, but now we consider it stretched (@fig-ch6a-stretchedsegment1). We can picture this as the string is "relaxed" in its 'horizontal' orientation (length of segment is $\Delta x$), but when a wave passes along it, the string elongates to accommodate the curve of the wave form. This means our segment now takes on a new length $\Delta l$.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![As the wave passes along a stretched string, we can consider it to be 'stretched'; considering a string element of lencth $\Delta x$, it is stretched to new length $\Delta l$ as the wave passes by.](visualisations/LaTeX/ch6a-peofstringsegment.svg){#fig-ch6a-stretchedsegment1 fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::


The work done (\Delta U) in stretching the segment $\Delta x$ can be expressed as:

$$
\Delta u = F(\Delta l - \Delta x)
$${#eq-ch6a-workdonestring1}

...where $F$ is the tension in the string and the extension is given by $(\Delta l - \Delta x)$.  We can apply Pythagoras to relate $\Delta x$ and $\Delta l$:

$$
\begin{array}{rcl}
\Delta l^2 &=& \Delta x^2 + \Delta y^2 \\
&=& \Delta x^2 \left[ 1 + \left( \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\right)^2 \right]
\end{array}
$$

Therefore we can isolate $\Delta l$:

$$
\Delta l = \Delta x \left[ 1 + \left( \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\right)^2 \right]^{\frac{1}{2}}
$$

We can approximate this expression by using the Taylor series expansion for $\sqrt{1+n}$, where $n = \left( \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\right)^2$; assuming that the fraction is significantly less than one we can write this as an approximation and disregard terms past the first two terms:^[The Taylor expansion for this expression is $\sqrt{1+n} = 1+ \frac{n}{2} - \frac{n^2}{8} + \frac{n^3}{16} - \cdots$]

$$
\Delta l \approx \Delta x \left[ 1 + \frac{1}{2}\left( \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\right)^2 + \cdots \right]
$$

Rearranging this expression to obtain the expression for the extension of the string $\Delta l - \Delta x$:

$$
\Delta l - \Delta x \approx   + \frac{\Delta x}{2} \left( \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\right)^2 + \cdots
$$

This now allows us to obtain an expression for the work done in stretching the spring solely in terms of the $x$ and $y$ displacement (from @eq-ch6a-workdonestring1)

$$
\Delta U = \frac{F\Delta x}{2} \left( \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\right)^2
$$


As we have an expression for $y$ in terms of $x$ (@eq-tranversesine2), we can differentiate this with respect to $x$ to approximate $\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}$:

$$
\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} \simeq \frac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d} x} = kA \cos (kx - \omega t)
$$

We also know that $v^2 = \frac{F}{\mu}$ (from the wave equation), and that $v = \frac{\omega}{k}$ (@eq-ch6a-phasevel1), therefore:

$$
\Delta U = \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{\mu \omega^2}{k^2} \right) \Delta x \left( kA \cos (kx - \omega t) \right)^2
$$

Tidying up and cancelling, we obtain the expression for the potential energy stored in an element of string of length $\Delta x$ (@eq-ch6a-pestoredstring1):

$$
\Delta U = \frac{1}{2} \mu \omega^2 A^2 \Delta x \cos^2(kx-\omega t)
$${#eq-ch6a-pestoredstring1}

### Kinetic energy of string segment {#sec-ch6a-keofstringsegment}

We will again consider the segment of string discussed in @sec-ch6a-peofstringsegment; an element $\Delta x$ of the string, of mass $\Delta m$ (@fig-ch6a-kestringsegment).


::: {.cell layout-align="center" auto_pdf='true'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Similar to the situation shown above, the same string segment will have a kinetic energy associated with its velocity $v_y$.](visualisations/LaTeX/ch6a-keofstringsegment.svg){#fig-ch6a-kestringsegment fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::


<!-- Figure \\@ref(ch6a-stretchedsegment1) -->

As before, the segment is stretched to new length $\Delta l$, but the mass is still given by:

$$
\Delta m = \mu \Delta x
$$

...where $\mu$ is the mass per unit length.  We now use the **transverse velocity** of the segment (*i.e.* **not** the wave velocity) to determine the kinetic energy of the segment:

$$
\Delta KE = \frac{1}{2} \Delta m v_y^2 = \frac{1}{2} \mu \Delta x \left( \frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} \right)^2
$$

Again, we know the expression for the vertical displacement $y$ in terms of $x$ and $t$ (@eq-tranversesine2), so we now differentiate with respect to $t$:

* $y = A \sin(kx - \omega t)$
* $v_y = \frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} = -\omega A \cos(kx - \omega t)$

Therefore our expression for the kinetic energy becomes:

$$
\Delta KE =  \frac{1}{2} \mu \omega^2  A^2 \Delta x  \cos^2(kx - \omega t)
$${#eq-ch6a-kestoredstring1}

A quick comparison of @eq-ch6a-pestoredstring1 and @eq-ch6a-kestoredstring1 shows that these expressions are identical; *i.e.* the KE stored in the string is the **same** as the PE stored in the spring.

### Total energy of wave on a string {#sec-ch6a-totenergystringsegment}

We can therefore find the total energy of the string segment carrying a harmonic wave as the total of the kinetic and potential energies:

$$
\Delta E = \Delta KE + \Delta U
$$

*i.e.*:

$$
\Delta E = \mu \omega^2  A^2 \Delta x  \cos^2(kx - \omega t)
$${#eq-ch6a-totalenergywavestring1}

Note that the energy of the segment varies with time with twice the frequency of the wave (since $\cos^2 \theta = \frac{1}{2}(1+ \cos 2\theta)$).  

We can also define the average energy at any point (@eq-ch6a-averageenergystring1) using the time-average definition $\left< \cos^2 \theta \right> = \frac{1}{2}$:

$$
\Delta E_{\mathrm{av}} = \frac{1}{2}\mu \omega^2 A^2 \Delta x
$${#eq-ch6a-averageenergystring1}

...and we can define the average *energy density* (per unit length) as:

$$
\varepsilon = \frac{\Delta E_{\mathrm{av}}}{\Delta x} = \frac{1}{2} \mu \omega^2 A^2
$$

There are several things to note from this derivation:

* KE is at a maximum when displacement is zero
* At this point the string is most stretched, so PE is at a maximum also
<!-- WHY??? Surely at zero displacement the string flat lines, so ∆l = ∆x, no stretching?? -->
<!-- No - stretching is proportional to gradient; gradient steepest at zero displacement. -->
* PE and KE are **in phase** (unlike in a pendulum)

These points are illustrated in @fig-ch6a-kepestringplot1.


